# Genie Platform — Architecture, CI/CD & Review Process Walkthrough
**Date:** 02 Jul 2026 · **Confidential — internal OATI/Genie**

## Purpose
Walkthrough of the target Genie platform model: how it should be packaged and deployed, the GitLab CI/CD pipeline, code-review standards, configuration management, and standard project structure. Positioned against the existing Web Vision bundled model. Points discussed are directional, not finalized.

## 1. Platform architecture & packaging
- Genie is built as **independent, individually versioned Python packages** (services, utility libraries, and default agents), in contrast to Web Vision's single bundled release.
- **Trade-off discussed:** independent versioning lets one module get a fix without pulling unrelated changes, but Web Vision's bundle guarantees all modules are certified and released together at a known-good version level.
- **Key risk / responsibility:** modules must stay backward compatible. Version bumps follow semantic-versioning intent — a breaking change requires bumping the major version and adding a migration/reason note. Ensuring cross-module version compatibility (e.g. module-1 vX certified against module-2 vY) becomes the **platform team's ongoing responsibility**; previously it was easier under one shared ISO infrastructure.
- Platform is treated as a **library set consumed by applications**, not a monolith that gets deployed as one thing. It provides: base agent classes + utility libraries, common services, and **ready-made default agents** (e.g. generic RAG agent, generic rule agent).

## 2. Deployment model
- Applications may spin up their **own Genie instance** — potentially with only the module(s) they need.
- Instances are **multi-tenant in some cases** (e.g. tagging, voice) and **dedicated per use case in others**.
- An application using only the default agents may need little to no custom code — often just deploying a new instance (plus DB/config as needed). The Web Vision framework's model was noted as not directly applicable here.

## 3. Package registry
- All releases published to the internal registry with visible version history; installed as standard Python packages via `pip`/`uv add`.

## 4. CI/CD pipeline (GitLab)
- **Pre-commit hooks (local):** auto-format, lint, and flag code-quality issues before commit. Every project must include the pre-commit config; developers run it locally and fix issues before pushing.
- **Pipeline stages:** lint → test (unit / integration / end-to-end via pytest markers) → deploy. **Deploy is currently commented out / not yet working.**
- Pipeline runs on merge requests (and ideally should run on all branches). An MR must pass before it is eligible for review.
- **Setup per project:** a project access token plus the required CI/CD variables must be configured (request token creation from the JNET team / Joe).
- **Required project files:** pre-commit config, `.gitignore`, README (setup steps + how to run + commands), `.python-version`, tests with unit/integration markers, and a CHANGELOG.

## 5. Code review process & standards
- Reviewers should **not** spend effort on syntax/formatting — that is handled by pre-commit/tooling. Focus should be on **what the code actually does** (logic, correctness).
- MR must be green (pipeline passing) before a reviewer engages.
- **Size discipline:** keep MRs small (target ≈50 lines, not a hard rule yet); avoid large end-of-work dumps. Break continuous work into incremental MRs. Reviewing a 10,000-line MR is impractical — a concern amplified by AI-generated code volume.
- GitLab currently allows **only one reviewer at a time**; multiple reviewers must go sequentially.
- **Action:** create a Genie-specific review **workflow + checklist** (adapt the detailed one already built for the Web Vision team, minus TFS/Web Vision-specifics) and publish it on the GitLab project.

## 6. Configuration management
- Config via `.env` or `config.yml`; **`.env` takes precedence** over `config.yml`.
- Ship a **`.env.example`** so that missing credentials/config fail loudly rather than breaking silently at runtime.

## 7. Internal common library
- An internal shared package ("any-common") provides logging, common classes, and ML Flow setup, reused across modules. Installed like any package; it is **not deployable itself** — it is used to build deployable code. Every project integrates it (e.g. ML Flow).

## 8. Standard project / folder structure
- Package layout standardized (managed with **UV**, replacing the older tool). Typical structure: `api/` (health endpoint + any exposed endpoints), core logic (nodes, prompts, graph builder), `models/` (Pydantic), `services/` (e.g. LLM), Dockerfile (deployed via gunicorn + uvicorn), and a CLI to run the service.
- **Consistent naming conventions across all projects** so reviewers can navigate any repo predictably (e.g. always call it the graph builder).

